{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d1ba5fc9-effe-4dc2-99af-6b2a88e521ba","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\n```jsonc\n// .vscode/mcp.json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — builds and launches your server automatically.\n- Your server must read JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport). Make sure any logging goes to **stderr**, not stdout.\n- Place this file at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root.\n\nIf you've published the server as a tool or have a compiled DLL, you can replace `dotnet run --project ...` with `dotnet exec path/to/MyMcpServer.dll` for faster startup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2958d2f5-ba14-4a31-abb4-66312ee6e128","outputTokens":302,"requestId":"5C50:D447C:1D0B389:202844B:69FA933A"},"id":"5ba6a00b-4020-4063-a7cd-4545d4169ea7","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:02:59.534Z","parentId":"f9264165-a878-4699-b5e2-acac552608a7"}
